          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Failed coalition and resignation </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-6-2.jpg" alt="Failed coalition and resignation" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Austria faces political uncertainty after Chancellor Karl Nehammer resigned, citing <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-h2-4-failed-coalition-talks" target="_blank">failed coalition talks</a> between the Austrian People's Party and the Social Democrats. Nehammer criticized the Social Democrats for their radical policies, while Social Democrat party leader Andreas Babler accused the Austrian People’s Party of tactical gamesmanship. A few days ago, the Austrian Liberal Party NEOS <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-h2-5-pulled-out" target="_blank">pulled out</a> of the coalition discussions due to frustrations with both parties over budget and competitiveness.  </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The talks aimed to form a centrist coalition to exclude the far-right Freedom Party, which emerged as the strongest party in <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-h2-6-september-elections" target="_blank">September's elections</a> with 29%. Nehammer's departure opens the door for potential collaboration between the Freedom Party and the Austrian People’s Party, though it risks polarizing Austrian politics. The interim leader of the Austrian People’s Party announced that he was <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-h2-7-willing-to-meet" target="_blank">willing to meet</a> with the head of the Freedom Party.​</p>
        </mj-text>
