          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is Jimmy Carter remembered for?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-6-3.jpg" alt="foundations" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Many remember <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-f1-12-jimmy-carter" target="_blank">Jimmy Carter</a> for his presidency and post-presidency work advancing peace, democracy, human rights, and the fight against poverty. He was an avid supporter of <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-f1-13-habitat-for-humanity" target="_blank">Habitat for Humanity</a> and was seen working for them in his last stages of life before he went to hospice. He also spent years advocating for social causes and trying to be on the right side. Many Republicans and Democrats alike have positive things to say about him. Carter was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for his ‘untiring effort to find peaceful solutions to international conflicts, to advance democracy and human rights and to promote economic and social development.’​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Many say, "Carter was a great person but not a great president.”  However, this is questionable, given the challenges of his presidency. Jimmy Carter was less of an interventionist president when US interventionism was peaking. While his presidency was marked by economic challenges, including long petrol queues, high unemployment, and the Iran hostage crisis, his legacy includes the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-f1-14-camp-david-accords" target="_blank">Camp David Accords</a>, which brokered peace between Egypt and Israel. Despite mixed results, he championed human rights as a key foreign policy priority, particularly in the Middle East.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">While some of his presidency's failures were not under his 100% control, such as the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-f1-15-iran-hostage-crisis" target="_blank">Iran hostage crisis</a>, it didn’t earn him a second presidency; he lost a landslide to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 election. But he kept doing his work after his presidency. After his defeat, he opened the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-01-2025-f1-16-carter-center" target="_blank">Carter Center</a> with his wife, Rosalynn Carter. The Carter Center aims to improve people's lives in dozens of countries by resolving conflicts, advancing democracy and human rights, preventing diseases, and improving mental health care.​</p>
        </mj-text>
